  "opinion": "As a 77-year-old retired man living in Los Angeles, I've seen a lot change over the years, and social media is one of those things that sometimes worries me, especially with all the fake content floating around. I'm not on social media much—just a few times a week—mostly to keep in touch with family and friends or see what's happening in my community. Given my background as an immigrant and my Christian beliefs, I value honesty and trust, so fake news and misleading posts really bother me. They can spread fear and division, which isn't good for anyone, especially when I already struggle with depression at times. To manage fake content, I think it's important to take a cautious approach. I don't click on everything I see; instead, I check sources by looking at reputable news sites or asking people I trust, like my wife or fellow volunteers at the local church. My hobbies, like volunteering and playing board games, have taught me to think things through carefully, so I apply that to social media too. I avoid sharing posts unless I'm sure they're true, and I report suspicious content when I can. It's also helpful to limit my time online, focusing more on real-life interactions, which keeps me grounded. Social media companies should do more to filter out lies, but until then, we all have a responsibility to be careful and not let fake stories upset us. By staying informed through reliable channels and leaning on my faith for guidance, I find I can navigate these digital waters without getting too overwhelmed.",
